        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Dumbola Lodge | Freshwater | Isle of Water<ref target="#foot.f2"/></placeName>
                    <date>July 23<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Huxley</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>You will see where we are. I got so bad that I could do nothing &amp; we have all come here for five weeks.— Will you have the kindness to tell Prof. Kühne, &amp; say how much pleased &amp; honoured I feel that he sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. have wished to have seen me.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I regret that this is impossible.—</p>
<p>From your note, I hope that you have stood well all your work &amp; this killing hot weather.<ref target="#foot.f4"/> You must, however, long for rest, &amp; M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Huxley<ref target="#foot.f5"/> must long for it still more for your sake.—</p>
<p>Ever my dear Huxley, yours most truly | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to the Darwins’ stay at Freshwater, Isle of Wight (<ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242)).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The name of the house was Dimbola Lodge; Isle of Water is a mistake for Isle of Wight.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2632.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Wilhelm Friedrich Kühne</ref>; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6283.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from T. H. Huxley, 20 July 1868</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">The summer of 1868 saw prolonged drought and unusually hot weather; according to the <hi rend="italic">Gardeners’ Chronicle</hi>, 8 August 1868, p. 843, the hottest days in July were the 21st and 22d, with the temperature near London 93<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>F (34<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>C). According to a later report, on 22 July a beef-steak was cooked on the south side of Westminster Bridge in twenty minutes by the heat of the sun’s rays alone (<hi rend="italic">Gardeners’ Chronicle</hi>, 17 October 1868, p. 1096).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2478.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Henrietta Anne Huxley</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
